# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: video-codec-h264
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] H.264 was standardized by the ITU-T Video Coding Experts Group (VCEG) of Study Group 16 together with the ISO/IEC JTC 1 Moving Picture Experts Group (MPEG).
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] The project partnership effort is known as the Joint Video Team (JVT).
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] The ITU-T H.264 standard and the ISO/IEC MPEG-4 AVC standard (formally, ISO/IEC 14496-10 – MPEG-4 Part 10, Advanced Video Coding) are jointly maintained so that they have identical technical content.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] The final drafting work on the first version of the standard was completed in May 2003, and various extensions of its capabilities have been added in subsequent editions.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] High Efficiency Video Coding (HEVC), a.k.a.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] H.265 and MPEG-H Part 2 is a successor to H.264/MPEG-4 AVC developed by the same organizations, while earlier standards are still in common use.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] H.264 is perhaps best known as being the most commonly used video encoding format on Blu-ray Discs.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] H.264 is restricted by patents owned by various parties.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] A license covering most (but not all) patents essential to H.264 is administered by a patent pool formerly administered by MPEG LA.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] Via Licensing Corp acquired MPEG LA in April 2023 and formed a new patent pool administration company called Via Licensing Alliance.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] The commercial use of patented H.264 technologies requires the payment of royalties to Via and other patent owners.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] MPEG LA has allowed the free use of H.264 technologies for streaming Internet video that is free to end users, and Cisco paid royalties to MPEG LA on behalf of the users of binaries for its open source H.264 encoder openH264.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] The H.264 name follows the ITU-T naming convention, where Recommendations are given a letter corresponding to their series and a recommendation number within the series.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] H.264 is part of "H-Series Recommendations: Audiovisual and multimedia systems".
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] H.264 is further categorized into "H.200-H.499: Infrastructure of audiovisual services" and "H.260-H.279: Coding of moving video".
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] The MPEG-4 AVC name relates to the naming convention in ISO/IEC MPEG, where the standard is part 10 of ISO/IEC 14496, which is the suite of standards known as MPEG-4.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] The standard was developed jointly in a partnership of VCEG and MPEG, after earlier development work in the ITU-T as a VCEG project called H.26L.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] It is thus common to refer to the standard with names such as H.264/AVC, AVC/H.264, H.264/MPEG-4 AVC, or MPEG-4/H.264 AVC, to emphasize the common heritage.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] Occasionally, it is also referred to as "the JVT codec", in reference to the Joint Video Team (JVT) organization that developed it.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] (Such partnership and multiple naming is not uncommon.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] For example, the video compression standard known as MPEG-2 also arose from the partnership between MPEG and the ITU-T, where MPEG-2 video is known to the ITU-T community as H.262.) Some software programs (such as VLC media player) internally identify this standard as AVC1.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] VCEG was chaired by Gary Sullivan (Microsoft, formerly PictureTel, U.S.).
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] The first draft design for that new standard was adopted in August 1999.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] In 2000, Thomas Wiegand (Heinrich Hertz Institute, Germany) became VCEG co-chair.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] In December 2001, VCEG and the Moving Picture Experts Group (MPEG – ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 29/WG 11) formed a Joint Video Team (JVT), with the charter to finalize the video coding standard.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] Formal approval of the specification came in March 2003.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] The JVT was (is) chaired by Gary Sullivan, Thomas Wiegand, and Ajay Luthra (Motorola, U.S.: later Arris, U.S.).
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] In July 2004, the Fidelity Range Extensions (FRExt) project was finalized.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] From January 2005 to November 2007, the JVT was working on an extension of H.264/AVC towards scalability by an Annex (G) called Scalable Video Coding (SVC).
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] The JVT management team was extended by Jens-Rainer Ohm (RWTH Aachen University, Germany).
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] From July 2006 to November 2009, the JVT worked on Multiview Video Coding (MVC), an extension of H.264/AVC towards 3D television and limited-range free-viewpoint television.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] That work included the development of two new profiles of the standard: the Multiview High Profile and the Stereo High Profile.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] Throughout the development of the standard, additional messages for containing supplemental enhancement information (SEI) have been developed.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] SEI messages can contain various types of data that indicate the timing of the video pictures or describe various properties of the coded video or how it can be used or enhanced.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] SEI messages are also defined that can contain arbitrary user-defined data.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] SEI messages do not affect the core decoding process, but can indicate how the video is recommended to be post-processed or displayed.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] Some other high-level properties of the video content are conveyed in video usability information (VUI), such as the indication of the color space for interpretation of the video content.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] As new color spaces have been developed, such as for high dynamic range and wide color gamut video, additional VUI identifiers have been added to indicate them.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] The standardization of the first version of H.264/AVC was completed in May 2003.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] In the first project to extend the original standard, the JVT then developed what was called the Fidelity Range Extensions (FRExt).
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] These extensions enabled higher quality video coding by supporting increased sample bit depth precision and higher-resolution color information, including the sampling structures known as Y′CBCR 4:2:2 (a.k.a.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] The design work on the FRExt project was completed in July 2004, and the drafting work on them was completed in September 2004.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] The next major feature added to the standard was Scalable Video Coding (SVC).
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] Specified in Annex G of H.264/AVC, SVC allows the construction of bitstreams that contain *layers* of sub-bitstreams that also conform to the standard, including one such bitstream known as the "base layer" that can be decoded by a H.264/AVC codec that does not support SVC.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] For temporal bitstream scalability (i.e., the presence of a sub-bitstream with a smaller temporal sampling rate than the main bitstream), complete access units are removed from the bitstream when deriving the sub-bitstream.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] In this case, high-level syntax and inter-prediction reference pictures in the bitstream are constructed accordingly.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] On the other hand, for spatial and quality bitstream scalability (i.e. the presence of a sub-bitstream with lower spatial resolution/quality than the main bitstream), the NAL (Network Abstraction Layer) is removed from the bitstream when deriving the sub-bitstream.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] In this case, inter-layer prediction (i.e., the prediction of the higher spatial resolution/quality signal from the data of the lower spatial resolution/quality signal) is typically used for efficient coding.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] The Scalable Video Coding extensions were completed in November 2007.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] The next major feature added to the standard was Multiview Video Coding (MVC).
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] Specified in Annex H of H.264/AVC, MVC enables the construction of bitstreams that represent more than one view of a video scene.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] An important example of this functionality is stereoscopic 3D video coding.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] Two profiles were developed in the MVC work: Multiview High profile supports an arbitrary number of views, and Stereo High profile is designed specifically for two-view stereoscopic video.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] The Multiview Video Coding extensions were completed in November 2009.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] Additional extensions were later developed that included 3D video coding with joint coding of depth maps and texture (termed 3D-AVC), multi-resolution frame-compatible (MFC) stereoscopic and 3D-MFC coding, various additional combinations of features, and higher frame sizes and frame rates.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] Versions of the H.264/AVC standard include the following completed revisions, corrigenda, and amendments (dates are final approval dates in ITU-T, while final "International Standard" approval dates in ISO/IEC are somewhat different and slightly later in most cases).
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] Each version represents changes relative to the next lower version that is integrated into the text.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] The H.264 video format has a very broad application range that covers all forms of digital compressed video from low bit-rate Internet streaming applications to HDTV broadcast and Digital Cinema applications with nearly lossless coding.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] With the use of H.264, bit rate savings of 50% or more compared to MPEG-2 Part 2 are reported.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] For example, H.264 has been reported to give the same Digital Satellite TV quality as current MPEG-2 implementations with less than half the bitrate, with current MPEG-2 implementations working at around 3.5 Mbit/s and H.264 at only 1.5 Mbit/s.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] Sony claims that 9 Mbit/s AVC recording mode is equivalent to the image quality of the HDV format, which uses approximately 18–25 Mbit/s.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] To ensure compatibility and problem-free adoption of H.264/AVC, many standards bodies have amended or added to their video-related standards so that users of these standards can employ H.264/AVC.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] Both the Blu-ray Disc format and the now-discontinued HD DVD format include the H.264/AVC High Profile as one of three mandatory video compression formats.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] The Digital Video Broadcast project (DVB) approved the use of H.264/AVC for broadcast television in late 2004.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] The Advanced Television Systems Committee (ATSC) standards body in the United States approved the use of H.264/AVC for broadcast television in July 2008.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] It has also been approved for use with the more recent ATSC-M/H (Mobile/Handheld) standard, using the AVC and SVC portions of H.264.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] The closed-circuit-television and video-surveillance markets have included the technology in many products.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] Many common DSLRs use H.264 video wrapped in QuickTime MOV containers as the native recording format.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] AVCHD is a high-definition recording format designed by Sony and Panasonic that uses H.264 (conforming to H.264 while adding additional application-specific features and constraints).
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] AVC-Intra is an intraframe-only compression format, developed by Panasonic.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] XAVC is a recording format designed by Sony that uses level 5.2 of H.264/MPEG-4 AVC, which is the highest level supported by that video standard.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] XAVC can support 4K resolution (4096 × 2160 and 3840 × 2160) at up to 60 frames per second (fps).
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] Sony has announced that cameras that support XAVC include two CineAlta cameras—the Sony PMW-F55 and Sony PMW-F5.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] The Sony PMW-F55 can record XAVC with 4K resolution at 30 fps at 300 Mbit/s and 2K resolution at 30 fps at 100 Mbit/s.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] XAVC can record 4K resolution at 60 fps with 4:2:2 chroma sampling at 600 Mbit/s.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] H.264/AVC/MPEG-4 Part 10 contains a number of new features that allow it to compress video much more efficiently than older standards and to provide more flexibility for application to a wide variety of network environments.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] These techniques, along with several others, help H.264 to perform significantly better than any prior standard under a wide variety of circumstances in a wide variety of application environments.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] H.264 can often perform radically better than MPEG-2 video—typically obtaining the same quality at half of the bit rate or less, especially on high bit rate and high resolution video content.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] Like other ISO/IEC MPEG video standards, H.264/AVC has a reference software implementation that can be freely downloaded.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] Its main purpose is to give examples of H.264/AVC features, rather than being a useful application *per se*.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] Some reference hardware design work has also been conducted in the Moving Picture Experts Group.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] The above-mentioned aspects include features in all profiles of H.264.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] A profile for a codec is a set of features of that codec identified to meet a certain set of specifications of intended applications.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] This means that many of the features listed are not supported in some profiles.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] Various profiles of H.264/AVC are discussed in next section.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] The standard defines several sets of capabilities, which are referred to as *profiles*, targeting specific classes of applications.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] These are declared using a profile code (profile_idc) and sometimes a set of additional constraints applied in the encoder.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] The profile code and indicated constraints allow a decoder to recognize the requirements for decoding that specific bitstream.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] (And in many system environments, only one or two profiles are allowed to be used, so decoders in those environments do not need to be concerned with recognizing the less commonly used profiles.) By far the most commonly used profile is the High Profile.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] Primarily for low-cost applications, this profile is most typically used in videoconferencing and mobile applications.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] It corresponds to the subset of features that are in common between the Baseline, Main, and High Profiles.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] Primarily for low-cost applications that require additional data loss robustness, this profile is used in some videoconferencing and mobile applications.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] This profile includes all features that are supported in the Constrained Baseline Profile, plus three additional features that can be used for loss robustness (or for other purposes such as low-delay multi-point video stream compositing).
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] The importance of this profile has faded somewhat since the definition of the Constrained Baseline Profile in 2009.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] All Constrained Baseline Profile bitstreams are also considered to be Baseline Profile bitstreams, as these two profiles share the same profile identifier code value.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] Intended as the streaming video profile, this profile has relatively high compression capability and some extra tricks for robustness to data losses and server stream switching.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] This profile is used for standard-definition digital TV broadcasts that use the MPEG-4 format as defined in the DVB standard.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] It is not, however, used for high-definition television broadcasts, as the importance of this profile faded when the High Profile was developed in 2004 for that application.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] Similar to the High profile, but without support of field coding features.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] Similar to the Progressive High profile, but without support of B (bi-predictive) slices.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] Going beyond typical mainstream consumer product capabilities, this profile builds on top of the High Profile, adding support for up to 10 bits per sample of decoded picture precision.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] format while using up to 10 bits per sample of decoded picture precision.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] This profile builds on top of the High 4:2:2 Profile, supporting up to 4:4:4 chroma sampling, up to 14 bits per sample, and additionally supporting efficient lossless region coding and the coding of each picture as three separate color planes.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] For camcorders, editing, and professional applications, the standard contains four additional Intra-frame-only profiles, which are defined as simple subsets of other corresponding profiles.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] The High 10 Profile constrained to all-Intra use.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] The High 4:2:2 Profile constrained to all-Intra use.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] The High 4:4:4 Profile constrained to all-Intra use.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] The High 4:4:4 Profile constrained to all-Intra use and to CAVLC entropy coding (i.e., not supporting CABAC).
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] Primarily targeting video conferencing, mobile, and surveillance applications, this profile builds on top of the Constrained Baseline profile to which the base layer (a subset of the bitstream) must conform.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] For the scalability tools, a subset of the available tools is enabled.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] A subset of the Scalable Baseline Profile intended primarily for real-time communication applications.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] Primarily targeting broadcast and streaming applications, this profile builds on top of the H.264/AVC High Profile to which the base layer must conform.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] A subset of the Scalable High Profile intended primarily for real-time communication applications.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] Primarily targeting production applications, this profile is the Scalable High Profile constrained to all-Intra use.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] 3D video and combines the tools of the High profile with the inter-view prediction capabilities of the MVC extension.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] This profile supports two or more views using both inter-picture (temporal) and MVC inter-view prediction, but does not support field pictures and macroblock-adaptive frame-field coding.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] A profile for stereoscopic coding with two-layer resolution enhancement.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] This profile supports joint coding of depth map and video texture information for improved compression of 3D video content.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] An enhanced profile for combined multiview coding with depth information.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] As the term is used in the standard, a "*level*" is a specified set of constraints that indicate a degree of required decoder performance for a profile.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] For example, a level of support within a profile specifies the maximum picture resolution, frame rate, and bit rate that a decoder may use.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] A decoder that conforms to a given level must be able to decode all bitstreams encoded for that level and all lower levels.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] The maximum bit rate for the High Profile is 1.25 times that of the Constrained Baseline, Baseline, Extended and Main Profiles; 3 times for Hi10P, and 4 times for Hi422P/Hi444PP.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] The number of luma samples is 16×16=256 times the number of macroblocks (and the number of luma samples per second is 256 times the number of macroblocks per second).
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] Previously encoded pictures are used by H.264/AVC encoders to provide predictions of the values of samples in other pictures.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] This allows the encoder to make efficient decisions on the best way to encode a given picture.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] At the decoder, such pictures are stored in a virtual *decoded picture buffer* (DPB).
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] This formula is specified in sections A.3.1.h and A.3.2.f of the 2017 edition of the standard.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] For example, for an HDTV picture that is 1,920 samples wide (PicWidthInMbs = 120) and 1,080 samples high (FrameHeightInMbs = 68), a Level 4 decoder has a maximum DPB storage capacity of floor(32768/(120*68)) = 4 frames (or 8 fields).
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] Thus, the value 4 is shown in parentheses in the table above in the right column of the row for Level 4 with the frame size 1920×1080.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] The current picture being decoded is *not included* in the computation of DPB fullness (unless the encoder has indicated for it to be stored for use as a reference for decoding other pictures or for delayed output timing).
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p01] Thus, a decoder needs to actually have sufficient memory to handle (at least) one frame *more* than the maximum capacity of the DPB as calculated above.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p02] In 2009, the HTML5 working group was split between supporters of Ogg Theora, a free video format which is thought to be unencumbered by patents, and H.264, which contains patented technology.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p02] As late as July 2009, Google and Apple were said to support H.264, while Mozilla and Opera support Ogg Theora (eventually Google, Mozilla and Opera all supported Theora and WebM with VP8, although Theora support was removed in 2023–2024).
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p02] Microsoft, with the release of Internet Explorer 9, has added support for HTML 5 video encoded using H.264.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p02] On March 18, 2012, Mozilla announced support for H.264 in Firefox on mobile devices, due to prevalence of H.264-encoded video and the increased power-efficiency of using dedicated H.264 decoder hardware common on such devices.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p02] On February 20, 2013, Mozilla implemented support in Firefox for decoding H.264 on Windows 7 and above.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p02] This feature relies on Windows' built in decoding libraries.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p02] Firefox 35.0, released on January 13, 2015, supports H.264 on OS X 10.6 and higher.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p02] However, any software projects that use Cisco's source code instead of its binaries would be legally responsible for paying all royalties to MPEG LA.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p02] Target CPU architectures include x86 and ARM, and target operating systems include Linux, Windows XP and later, Mac OS X, and Android; iOS was notably absent from this list, because it does not allow applications to fetch and install binary modules from the Internet.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p02] Also on October 30, 2013, Brendan Eich from Mozilla wrote that it would use Cisco's binaries in future versions of Firefox to add support for H.264 to Firefox where platform codecs are not available.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p02] Cisco published the source code to OpenH264 on December 9, 2013.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p02] Although iOS was not supported by the 2013 Cisco software release, Apple updated its Video Toolbox Framework with iOS 8 (released in September 2014) to provide direct access to hardware-based H.264/AVC video encoding and decoding.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p02] Because H.264 encoding and decoding require significant computational power for specific arithmetic operations, software implementations running on general-purpose CPUs are typically less power-efficient.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p02] However, consumer-grade CPUs with 6 or 8 cores since around 2016, and quad-core general-purpose x86 CPUs as of January 2020 have sufficient computation power to perform real-time SD and HD encoding.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p02] Compression efficiency depends on video algorithmic implementations, not on whether hardware or software implementation is used.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p02] Therefore, the difference between hardware and software based implementation is more on power-efficiency, flexibility and cost.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p02] To improve the power efficiency and reduce hardware form-factor, special-purpose hardware may be employed, either for the complete encoding or decoding process, or for acceleration assistance within a CPU-controlled environment.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p02] CPU based solutions are known to be much more flexible, particularly when encoding must be done concurrently in multiple formats, multiple bit rates and resolutions (multi-screen video), and possibly with additional features on container format support, advanced integrated advertising features, etc.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p02] CPU based software solution generally makes it much easier to load balance multiple concurrent encoding sessions within the same CPU.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p02] The 2nd generation Intel "Sandy Bridge" Core i3/i5/i7 processors introduced at the January 2011 CES (Consumer Electronics Show) offer an on-chip hardware full HD H.264 encoder, known as Intel Quick Sync Video.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p02] A hardware H.264 encoder can be an ASIC or an FPGA.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p02] Some companies have both FPGA and ASIC product offerings.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p02] Texas Instruments manufactures a line of ARM + DSP cores that perform DSP H.264 BP encoding 1080p at 30 fps.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p02] This permits flexibility with respect to codecs (which are implemented as highly optimized DSP code) while being more efficient than software on a generic CPU.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p02] In countries where patents on software algorithms are upheld, vendors and commercial users of products that use H.264/AVC are expected to pay patent licensing royalties for the patented technology that their products use.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p02] This applies to the Baseline Profile as well.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p02] A private organization known as Via-LA administers the licenses for patents applying to this standard, as well as other patent pools, such as for MPEG-4 Part 2 Video, HEVC and MPEG-DASH.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p02] On August 26, 2010, MPEG-LA announced that royalties would not be charged for H.264 encoded Internet video that is free to end users.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p02] All other royalties remain in place, such as royalties for products that decode and encode H.264 video as well as to operators of free television and subscription channels.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p02] The license terms are updated in 5-year blocks.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p02] In 2005, Qualcomm sued Broadcom in US District Court, alleging that Broadcom infringed on two of its patents by making products that were compliant with the H.264 video compression standard.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p02] In 2007, the District Court found that the patents were unenforceable because Qualcomm had failed to disclose them to the JVT prior to the release of the H.264 standard in May 2003.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p02] In December 2008, the US Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit affirmed the District Court's order that the patents be unenforceable but remanded to the District Court with instructions to limit the scope of unenforceability to H.264 compliant products.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p02] In October 2023 Nokia sued HP and Amazon for H.264/H.265 patent infringement in USA, UK and other locations.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p02] In February 2026, the VIA Licensing Authority announced a new licensing scheme targeting video streaming that applies to version 4 of the h264 specification and later.
[src:video-codec-h264/advanced-video-coding-p02] This changes the terms for new licensees after January 2026.
[src:video-codec-h264/context-adaptive-binary-arithmetic-coding] CABAC is also difficult to parallelize and vectorize, so other forms of parallelism (such as spatial region parallelism) may be coupled with its use.
[src:video-codec-h264/context-adaptive-binary-arithmetic-coding] In HEVC, CABAC is used in all profiles of the standard.
[src:video-codec-h264/context-adaptive-binary-arithmetic-coding] CABAC has multiple probability modes for different contexts.
[src:video-codec-h264/context-adaptive-binary-arithmetic-coding] It first converts all non-binary symbols to binary.
[src:video-codec-h264/context-adaptive-binary-arithmetic-coding] Then, for each bit, the coder selects which probability model to use, then uses information from nearby elements to optimize the probability estimate.
[src:video-codec-h264/context-adaptive-binary-arithmetic-coding] Arithmetic coding is finally applied to compress the data.
[src:video-codec-h264/context-adaptive-binary-arithmetic-coding] The context modeling provides estimates of conditional probabilities of the coding symbols.
[src:video-codec-h264/context-adaptive-binary-arithmetic-coding] Utilizing suitable context models, a given inter-symbol redundancy can be exploited by switching between different probability models according to already-coded symbols in the neighborhood of the current symbol to encode.
[src:video-codec-h264/context-adaptive-binary-arithmetic-coding] The context modeling is responsible for most of CABAC's roughly 10% savings in bit rate over the CAVLC entropy coding method.
[src:video-codec-h264/context-adaptive-binary-arithmetic-coding] Coding a data symbol involves the following stages.
[src:video-codec-h264/context-adaptive-binary-arithmetic-coding] The first bit of the binarized codeword is bin 1; the second bit is bin 2; and so on.
[src:video-codec-h264/context-adaptive-binary-arithmetic-coding] One of 3 models is selected for bin 1, based on previous coded MVD values.
[src:video-codec-h264/context-adaptive-binary-arithmetic-coding] If ek is small, then there is a high probability that the current MVD will have a small magnitude; conversely, if ek is large then it is more likely that the current MVD will have a large magnitude.
[src:video-codec-h264/context-adaptive-binary-arithmetic-coding] We select a probability table (context model) accordingly.
[src:video-codec-h264/context-adaptive-binary-arithmetic-coding] The selected context model supplies two probability estimates: the probability that the bin contains "1" and the probability that the bin contains "0".
[src:video-codec-h264/context-adaptive-binary-arithmetic-coding] These estimates determine the two sub-ranges that the arithmetic coder uses to encode the bin.
[src:video-codec-h264/context-adaptive-binary-arithmetic-coding] For example, if context model 2 was selected for bin 1 and the value of bin 1 was "0", the frequency count of "0"s is incremented.
[src:video-codec-h264/context-adaptive-binary-arithmetic-coding] This means that the next time this model is selected, the probability of a "0" will be slightly higher.
[src:video-codec-h264/context-adaptive-binary-arithmetic-coding] When the total number of occurrences of a model exceeds a threshold value, the frequency counts for "0" and "1" will be scaled down, which in effect gives higher priority to recent observations.
[src:video-codec-h264/context-adaptive-binary-arithmetic-coding] The arithmetic decoder is described in some detail in the Standard.
[src:video-codec-h264/context-adaptive-binary-arithmetic-coding] The range *R* representing the current state of the arithmetic coder is quantized to a small range of pre-set values before calculating the new range at each step, making it possible to calculate the new range using a look-up table (i.e. multiplication-free).
[src:video-codec-h264/context-adaptive-binary-arithmetic-coding] A simplified encoding and decoding process is defined for data symbols with a near uniform probability distribution.
[src:video-codec-h264/context-adaptive-binary-arithmetic-coding] The definition of the decoding process is designed to facilitate low-complexity implementations of arithmetic encoding and decoding.
[src:video-codec-h264/context-adaptive-binary-arithmetic-coding] Overall, CABAC provides improved coding efficiency compared with CAVLC-based coding, at the expense of greater computational complexity.
[src:video-codec-h264/context-adaptive-binary-arithmetic-coding] Mohiuddin and Jorma Johannes Rissanen filed a patent for a multiplication-free binary arithmetic coding algorithm.
[src:video-codec-h264/context-adaptive-binary-arithmetic-coding] In 1988, an IBM research team including R.B.
[src:video-codec-h264/context-adaptive-binary-arithmetic-coding] Langdon presented an adaptive binary arithmetic coding (ABAC) algorithm called Q-Coder.
[src:video-codec-h264/context-adaptive-binary-arithmetic-coding] The above patents and research papers, along several others from IBM and Mitsubishi Electric, were later cited by the CCITT and Joint Photographic Experts Group as the basis for the JPEG image compression format's adaptive binary arithmetic coding algorithm in 1992.
[src:video-codec-h264/context-adaptive-binary-arithmetic-coding] The first reported use of adaptive binary arithmetic coding in motion video compression was in a proposal by IBM researchers to the MPEG group in 1989.
[src:video-codec-h264/context-adaptive-binary-arithmetic-coding] This proposal extended the use of arithmetic coding from intraframe JPEG to interframe video coding.
[src:video-codec-h264/context-adaptive-binary-arithmetic-coding] In 1999, Youngjun Yoo (Texas Instruments), Young Gap Kwon and Antonio Ortega (University of Southern California) presented a context-adaptive form of binary arithmetic coding.
[src:video-codec-h264/context-adaptive-binary-arithmetic-coding] The modern context-adaptive binary arithmetic coding (CABAC) algorithm was commercially introduced with the H.264/MPEG-4 AVC format in 2003.
[src:video-codec-h264/context-adaptive-binary-arithmetic-coding] The majority of patents for the AVC format are held by Panasonic, Godo Kaisha IP Bridge and LG Electronics.
[src:video-codec-h264/group-of-pictures] In video coding, a **group of pictures**, or **GOP structure**, specifies the order in which intra- and inter-frames are arranged.
[src:video-codec-h264/group-of-pictures] The GOP is a collection of successive pictures within a coded video stream.
[src:video-codec-h264/group-of-pictures] Each coded video stream consists of successive GOPs, from which the visible frames are generated.
[src:video-codec-h264/group-of-pictures] Encountering a new GOP in a compressed video stream means that the decoder doesn't need any previous frames in order to decode the next ones, and allows fast seeking through the video.
[src:video-codec-h264/group-of-pictures] An I frame indicates the beginning of a GOP.
[src:video-codec-h264/group-of-pictures] Afterwards, several P and B frames follow.
[src:video-codec-h264/group-of-pictures] In older designs, the allowed ordering and referencing structure is relatively constrained.
[src:video-codec-h264/group-of-pictures] The I frames contain the full image and do not require any additional information to reconstruct them.
[src:video-codec-h264/group-of-pictures] Typically, encoders use GOP structures that cause each I frame to be a "clean random access point," such that decoding can start cleanly on an I frame and any errors within the GOP structure are corrected after processing a correct I frame.
[src:video-codec-h264/group-of-pictures] In the newer designs found in H.264/MPEG-4 AVC and HEVC, encoders have much more flexibility about referencing structures.
[src:video-codec-h264/group-of-pictures] They can use the same referencing structures as were previously used in older designs, or they can use more pictures as references and they can use more flexible ordering of the coding order relative to the display order.
[src:video-codec-h264/group-of-pictures] They are also allowed to use B frames as references when coding other (B or P) frames.
[src:video-codec-h264/group-of-pictures] This extra flexibility can improve compression efficiency, but it can cause propagation of errors if some data becomes lost or corrupted.
[src:video-codec-h264/group-of-pictures] One popular structure for use with the newer designs is the use of a hierarchy of B frames.
[src:video-codec-h264/group-of-pictures] Hierarchical B frames can provide very good compression efficiency and can also limit the propagation of errors, since the hierarchy can ensure that the number of pictures affected by any data corruption problem is strictly limited.
[src:video-codec-h264/group-of-pictures] Generally, the more I frames the video stream has, the more editable it is.
[src:video-codec-h264/group-of-pictures] However, having more I frames substantially increases bit rate needed to code the video.
[src:video-codec-h264/group-of-pictures] The GOP structure is often referred by two numbers, for example, *M*=3, *N*=12.
[src:video-codec-h264/group-of-pictures] The first number tells the distance between two anchor frames (I or P), also known as the length of a "mini-GOP".
[src:video-codec-h264/group-of-pictures] The second one tells the distance between two full images (I-frames): it is the GOP size.
[src:video-codec-h264/group-of-pictures] Instead of the M parameter, the maximal count of B-frames between two consecutive anchor frames can be used; this is the approach used by ffmpeg.
[src:video-codec-h264/group-of-pictures] The GOP structure does not need to stay fixed throughout encoding.
[src:video-codec-h264/group-of-pictures] Varying N to insert an I-frame on scene change is a well-known technique.
[src:video-codec-h264/group-of-pictures] Newer techniques also vary M based on the amount of motion in the video.
[src:video-codec-h264/group-of-pictures] With H.264 and later designs which allow highly flexible reference structures, a B frame in one GOP is able to reference a frame in a different GOP, in particular even before the I frame, which makes I frame non-IDR (not a keyframe).
[src:video-codec-h264/group-of-pictures] A GOP that contains any such outward-referencing frame is known as an "open GOP".
[src:video-codec-h264/group-of-pictures] The opposite is a self-contained GOP, known as a "closed GOP".
[src:video-codec-h264/group-of-pictures] In presentation order GOP can begin with a B-frame, but it cannot end with one.
[src:video-codec-h264/group-of-pictures] Open GOP starts with a B-frame and it is a little more efficient because starting with an I-frame means that an extra P-frame must be added to the end (a GOP cannot end with a B-frame).
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] An **inter frame** is a frame in a video compression stream which is expressed in terms of one or more neighboring frames.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] The "inter" part of the term refers to the use of *Inter frame prediction*.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] This tries to take advantage of temporal redundancy between neighboring frames, enabling higher compression rates.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] An inter coded frame is divided into blocks known as macroblocks.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] After that, instead of directly encoding the raw pixel values for each block, the encoder will try to find a block similar to the one it is encoding on a previously encoded frame, referred to as a reference frame.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] This process is done by a block matching algorithm.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] If the encoder succeeds on its search, the block could be encoded by a vector, known as motion vector, which points to the position of the matching block at the reference frame.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] The process of motion vector determination is called motion estimation.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] In most cases the encoder will succeed, but the block found is likely not an exact match to the block it is encoding.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] This is why the encoder will compute the differences between them.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] Those residual values are known as the prediction error and need to be transformed and sent to the decoder.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] To sum up, if the encoder succeeds in finding a matching block on a reference frame, it will obtain a motion vector pointing to the matched block and a prediction error.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] Using both elements, the decoder will be able to recover the raw pixels of the block.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] Because of these drawbacks, a reliable and time periodic reference frame must be used for this technique to be efficient and useful.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] That reference frame is known as Intra-frame, which is strictly intra coded, so it can always be decoded without additional information.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] In most designs, there are two types of inter frames: P-frames and B-frames.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] These two kinds of frames and the I-frames (Intra-coded pictures) usually join in a GOP (Group Of Pictures).
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] The I-frame doesn't need additional information to be decoded and it can be used as a reliable reference.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] This structure also allows to achieve an I-frame periodicity, which is needed for decoder synchronization.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] The difference between P-frames and B-frames is the reference frame they are allowed to use.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] P-frame is the term used to define the forward Predicted pictures.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] The prediction is made from an earlier picture, mainly an I-frame or P-frame, so that require less coding data (≈50% when compared to I-frame size).
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] The amount of data needed for doing this prediction consist of motion vectors and transform coefficients describing prediction correction.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] It involves the use of motion compensation.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] B-frame is the term for bidirectionally predicted pictures.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] This kind of prediction method occupies less coding data than P-frames generally (≈25% when compared to I-frame size) because the prediction is made from either an earlier frame or a later frame or both them.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] Similar to P-frames, B-frames are expressed as motion vectors and transform coefficients.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] In order to avoid a growing propagation error, B-frames are not used as a reference to make further predictions in most encoding standards.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] However, in newer encoding methods (such as H.264/MPEG-4 AVC and HEVC), B-frames may be used as reference for better exploitation of temporal redundancy.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] The typical Group of pictures (GOP) structure is IBBPBBP...
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] The I-frame is used to predict the first P-frame and these two frames are also used to predict the first and the second B-frames.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] The second P-frame is predicted also using the first I-frame.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] Both P-frames join to predict the third and fourth B-frames.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] This structure suggests a problem because the fourth frame (a P-frame) is needed in order to predict the second and the third (B-frames).
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] So we need to transmit the P-frame before the B-frames and it will delay the transmission (it will be necessary to keep the P-frame).
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] The last case allows the division of the block into new blocks of 4×8, 8×4, or 4×4.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] The frame to be coded is divided into blocks of equal size as shown in the picture above.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] Each block prediction will be blocks of the same size as the reference pictures, offset by a small displacement.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] Pixels at half-pixel position are obtained by applying a filter of length 6.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] Pixels at quarter-pixel position are obtained by bilinear interpolation.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] While MPEG-2 allowed a ½ pixel resolution, Inter frame allows up to ¼ pixel resolution.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] That means that it is possible to search a block in the frame to be coded in other reference frames, or we can interpolate nonexistent pixels to find blocks that are even better suited to the current block.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] If motion vector is an integer number of units of samples, that means it is possible to find in reference pictures the compensated block in motion.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] If motion vector is not an integer, the prediction will be obtained from interpolated pixels by an interpolator filter to horizontal and vertical directions.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] Multiple references to motion estimation allows finding the best reference in 2 possible buffers (List 0 to past pictures, List 1 to future pictures) which contain up to 16 frames in total.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] Block prediction is done by a weighted sum of blocks from the reference picture.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] It allows enhanced picture quality in scenes where there are changes of plane, zoom, or when new objects are revealed.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] Skip and Direct Mode are very frequently used, especially with B-frames.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] They significantly reduce the number of bits to be coded.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] These modes are referred to when a block is coded without sending residual error or motion vectors.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] The encoder will only record that it is a Skip Macroblock.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] The decoder will deduce the motion vector of Direct/Skip Mode coded block from other blocks already decoded.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] It uses the block motion vector from List 1 frame, located at the same position to deduce the motion vector.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] List 1 block uses a List 0 block as reference.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] It predicts the movement from neighbor macroblocks in same frame.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] A possible criterion could be to copy the motion vector from a neighboring block.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] These modes are used in uniform zones of the picture where there is not much movement.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] In the figure above, pink blocks are Direct/Skip Mode coded blocks.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] As we can see, they are used very frequently, mainly in B-frames.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] Video codecs such as MPEG-2, H.264 or Ogg Theora reduce the amount of data in a stream by following key frames with one or more inter frames.
[src:video-codec-h264/inter-frame] These frames can typically be encoded using a lower bit rate than is needed for key frames because much of the image is ordinarily similar, so only the changing parts need to be coded.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] Motion compensation is one of the two key video compression techniques used in video coding standards, along with the discrete cosine transform (DCT).
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] Most video coding standards, such as the H.26x and MPEG formats, typically use motion-compensated DCT hybrid coding, known as block motion compensation (BMC) or motion-compensated DCT (MC DCT).
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] Motion compensation exploits the fact that, often, for many frames of a movie, the only difference between one frame and another is the result of either the camera moving or an object in the frame moving.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] In reference to a video file, this means much of the information that represents one frame will be the same as the information used in the next frame.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] Using motion compensation, a video stream will contain some full (reference) frames; then, the only information stored for the frames in between would be the information needed to transform the previous frame into the next frame.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] The following is a simplistic illustrated explanation of how motion compensation works.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] Two successive frames were captured from the movie *Elephants Dream*.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] As can be seen from the images, the bottom (motion compensated) difference between two frames contains significantly less detail than the prior images, and thus compresses much better than the rest.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] In MPEG, images are predicted from previous frames (P frames) or bidirectionally from previous and future frames (B frames).
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] B frames are more complex because the image sequence must be transmitted and stored out of order so that the future frame is available to generate the B frames.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] After predicting frames using motion compensation, the coder finds the residual, which is then compressed and transmitted.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] It works best for still scenes without moving objects.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] MPEG-4 ASP supports global motion compensation with three reference points, although some implementations can only make use of one.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] A single reference point only allows for translational motion, which, for its relatively large performance cost, provides little advantage over block-based motion compensation.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] Moving objects within a frame are not sufficiently represented by global motion compensation.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] Thus, local motion estimation is also needed.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] To exploit the redundancy between neighboring block vectors (e.g., for a single moving object covered by multiple blocks), it is common to encode only the difference between the current and previous motion vector in the bit-stream.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] The result of this differentiating process is mathematically equivalent to a global motion compensation capable of panning.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] Further down the encoding pipeline, an entropy coder will take advantage of the resulting statistical distribution of the motion vectors around the zero vector to reduce the output size.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] It is possible to shift a block by a non-integer number of pixels, which is called *sub-pixel precision*.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] The in-between pixels are generated by interpolating neighboring pixels.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] Commonly, half-pixel or quarter-pixel precision (Qpel, used by H.264 and MPEG-4/ASP) is used.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] The computational expense of sub-pixel precision is much higher due to the extra processing required for interpolation and on the encoder side, a much greater number of potential source blocks to be evaluated.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] The main disadvantage of block motion compensation is that it introduces discontinuities at the block borders (blocking artifacts).
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] The source blocks typically overlap in the source frame.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] Some video compression algorithms assemble the current frame out of pieces of several different previously transmitted frames.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] Frames can also be predicted from future frames.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] The future frames then need to be encoded before the predicted frames and thus, the encoding order does not necessarily match the real frame order.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] Such frames are usually predicted from two directions, i.e., from the I- or P-frames that immediately precede or follow the predicted frame.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] These bidirectionally predicted frames are called *B-frames*.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] A coding scheme could, for instance, be IBBPBBPBBPBB.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] Further, the use of triangular tiles has also been proposed for motion compensation.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] Under this scheme, the frame is tiled with triangles, and the next frame is generated by performing an affine transformation on these triangles.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] Only the affine transformations are recorded/transmitted.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] This is capable of dealing with zooming, rotation, translation etc.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] Studies of methods for reducing the complexity of OBMC have shown that the contribution to the window function is smallest for the diagonally-adjacent block.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] Reducing the weight for this contribution to zero and increasing the other weights by an equal amount leads to a substantial reduction in complexity without a large penalty in quality.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] In such a scheme, each pixel then belongs to 3 blocks rather than 4, and rather than using 8 neighboring blocks, only 4 are used for each block to be compensated.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] In motion compensation, quarter or half samples are actually interpolated sub-samples caused by fractional motion vectors.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] Based on the vectors and full-samples, the sub-samples can be calculated by using bicubic or bilinear 2-D filtering.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] See subclause 8.4.2.2 "Fractional sample interpolation process" of the H.264 standard.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] Motion compensation is utilized in stereoscopic video coding.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] In video, *time* is often considered as the third dimension.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] Still, image coding techniques can be expanded to an extra dimension.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] JPEG 2000 uses wavelets, and these can also be used to encode motion without gaps between blocks in an adaptive way.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] Fractional pixel affine transformations lead to bleeding between adjacent pixels.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] If no higher internal resolution is used the delta images mostly fight against the image smearing out.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] The delta image can also be encoded as wavelets, so that the borders of the adaptive blocks match.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] 2D+Delta Encoding techniques utilize H.264 and MPEG-2 compatible coding and can use motion compensation to compress between stereoscopic images.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] A precursor to the concept of motion compensation dates back to 1929, when R.D.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] Kell in Britain proposed the concept of transmitting only the portions of an analog video scene that changed from frame-to-frame.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] In 1959, the concept of inter-frame motion compensation was proposed by NHK researchers Y.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] Tanaka, who proposed predictive inter-frame video coding in the temporal dimension.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] Practical motion-compensated video compression emerged with the development of motion-compensated DCT (MC DCT) coding, also called block motion compensation (BMC) or DCT motion compensation.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] This is a hybrid coding algorithm, which combines two key data compression techniques: discrete cosine transform (DCT) coding in the spatial dimension, and predictive motion compensation in the temporal dimension.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] DCT coding is a lossy block compression transform coding technique that was first proposed by Nasir Ahmed, who initially intended it for image compression, in 1972.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] In 1974, Ali Habibi at the University of Southern California introduced hybrid coding, which combines predictive coding with transform coding.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] However, his algorithm was initially limited to intra-frame coding in the spatial dimension.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] Robinson extended Habibi's hybrid coding algorithm to the temporal dimension, using transform coding in the spatial dimension and predictive coding in the temporal dimension, developing inter-frame motion-compensated hybrid coding.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] In 1977, Wen-Hsiung Chen developed a fast DCT algorithm with C.H.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] Jain further developed motion-compensated DCT video compression, also called block motion compensation.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] This led to Chen developing a practical video compression algorithm, called motion-compensated DCT or adaptive scene coding, in 1981.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] Motion-compensated DCT later became the standard coding technique for video compression from the late 1980s onwards.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] The first digital video coding standard was H.120, developed by the CCITT (now ITU-T) in 1984.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] H.120 used motion-compensated DPCM coding, which was inefficient for video coding, and H.120 was thus impractical due to low performance.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] The H.261 standard was developed in 1988 based on motion-compensated DCT compression, and it was the first practical video coding standard.
[src:video-codec-h264/motion-compensation] Since then, motion-compensated DCT compression has been adopted by all the major video coding standards (including the H.26x and MPEG formats) that followed.
